{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510107"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.27,0.15,0.42,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115602"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4123"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97605"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"99"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115602"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive shortness of breath. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, and a previous ST-elevation myocardial infarction treated with cardiac stenting. She still suffers from stable angina. Her medications include metformin, perindopril, atorvastatin, and aspirin. She does not have any allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 160/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. A pansystolic murmur is present, loudest at the apex. Her JVP is elevated at 7 cm. There is sacral and bilateral pitting lower limb oedema. Auscultation of the lung bases reveals reduced vocal resonance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional examination findings is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bilateral pleural rub and normal percussion note","Bilateral medium crackles and normal percussion note","Bilateral expiratory wheeze and dull percussion note","Bilateral bronchial breath sounds and dull percussion note","Bilateral fine inspiratory crackles and hyperresonant percussion note"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute decompensated heart failure leading to pulmonary oedema. The clinical features supporting this diagnosis include progressive dyspnoea, elevated JVP, peripheral oedema, and a pansystolic murmur consistent with mitral regurgitation. Mitral regurgitation can both cause and exacerbate heart failure, particularly in the setting of previous myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral medium crackles and normal percussion note\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. In pulmonary oedema, fluid accumulates in the alveoli and interstitium, producing medium (or moderate) crackles that are typically heard at the lung bases. These crackles result from the opening of fluid-filled alveoli during inspiration. The crackles associated with pulmonary oedema are typically described as medium or moderate in quality, not as harsh or coarse as those heard with infection or bronchiectasis. In acute presentations, the percussion note typically remains normal as significant pleural effusions take time to develop. The reduced vocal resonance already noted in the stem suggests some fluid accumulation, but dullness to percussion would be more likely in cases of persistent or severe pulmonary oedema with substantial pleural effusions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral pleural rub and normal percussion note\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest pleurisy, which can occur with pulmonary embolism, pneumonia, or uraemia. However, this would not explain the patient\u0027s signs of fluid overload and cardiac failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral expiratory wheeze and dull percussion note\u003C/strong\u003E is an unusual combination. Expiratory wheeze indicates airway obstruction as seen in asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, which typically causes hyperinflation and a hyperresonant percussion note, not dullness. However, it should be noted that \u0027cardiac wheeze\u0027 can occur in heart failure when pulmonary oedema causes airway narrowing, though this is typically accompanied by crackles rather than isolated wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral bronchial breath sounds and dull percussion note\u003C/strong\u003E suggests consolidation, as in pneumonia. However, bronchial breathing is usually unilateral and associated with increased (not decreased) vocal resonance. The bilateral nature and decreased vocal resonance make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral fine inspiratory crackles and hyperresonant percussion note\u003C/strong\u003E would be unusual. Fine crackles are characteristic of interstitial lung disease, while hyperresonance suggests air trapping or pneumothorax. This combination would not explain the acute presentation with signs of fluid overload.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute decompensated heart failure typically presents with dyspnoea, elevated JVP, peripheral oedema, and pulmonary congestion.","Pulmonary oedema produces bilateral medium crackles at the lung bases due to fluid-filled alveoli opening during inspiration.","A pansystolic murmur loudest at the apex suggests mitral regurgitation, which can precipitate or worsen heart failure."],"references":["Sarkar M, Madabhavi I, Niranjan N, Dogra M. Auscultation of the respiratory system. Ann Thorac Med. 2015 Jul-Sep;10(3):158-168. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4518345/","Boucher N, Pyrstupa A, Witczak A, Walczak E, Dzida G, Panasiuk L. Lung auscultation - identification of common sound abnormalities and associated pathologies. J Pre Clin Clin Res. 2013;7(1):32-35. Available from: http://www.jpccr.eu/Lung-auscultation-Identification-of-common-lung-sound-abnormalities-and-associated,71431,0,2.html","Honig E. An Overview of the Pulmonary System. In: Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, editors. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. 3rd edition. Boston: Butterworths; 1990. Chapter 35. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK356/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97605"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97605"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T15:28:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T18:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4123"}},"con